Title   : Consumption revival seen as the key driver amid global trade headwinds: Sajjid Chinoy 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-23T10:02:16
Fetched : 2025-09-24T02:10:13.237011
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/consumption-revival-seen-as-the-key-driver-amid-global-trade-headwinds-sajjid-chinoy/articleshow/124067825.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
On concerns around India’s widening trade deficits with BRICS nations, Chinoy said he does not view deficits as inherently negative. “I am not sure deficits necessarily are bad because by that logic, what the US is doing is also correct. Ultimately, a trade deficit or trade imbalance or a current account imbalance is simply the investment-savings gap of an economy. Running a sustainable current account deficit, 2% of GDP or 2.5% of GDP, is not a bad thing because it allows you to attract foreign capital and the technology that comes with it to augment your domestic savings,” he explained.
Turning to domestic demand, Chinoy highlighted five key factors that could drive private consumption in the months ahead. “First, we have got record low inflation this year. Second, we have had another very strong monsoon. Third, the monetary easing that the RBI has undertaken is working its way through the system. Fourth, we had direct tax cuts in the February budget. Fifth, we now have indirect tax cuts. All these factors are reinforcing each other,” he said.
He added that rural demand is already showing signs of recovery. “What has been very encouraging in the last six months is that you have seen clear signs that rural demand and rural consumption are picking up,” he observed. He believes that urban consumption should also benefit from lower lending rates, credit growth, and tax cuts.
On fiscal concerns arising from revenue foregone due to tax cuts, Chinoy noted, “There are a lot of moving parts and we are still early in the year. The key here will be that if growth begins to inflect in the coming quarters, then you should get both real growth picking up and hopefully buoyancy picks up in the coming months.”
When asked about RBI’s policy path, he stressed patience. “Right now, the central bank has the luxury to wait. They have frontloaded 100 basis points of easing. By December, we will have a much greater sense of where we are on the trade negotiations. If at that point more support is required, inflation is benign enough that if the RBI needs to use monetary policy in the coming months, it has the space.”
Chinoy also cautioned that topline growth will be critical for earnings recovery. “One cannot be at the mercy of just expecting input costs to go down. If consumption begins to pick up and that boosts topline growth in the next few quarters, that is what should help earnings pick up,” he said. With nominal GDP growth projected at around 8-9%, he emphasized that expectations for earnings, credit, and tax collections must be anchored accordingly.
