Title   : Private defence firms poised to grow 16-18% in FY26, order books seen at Rs 55,000 crore: Crisil 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-23T09:36:04
Fetched : 2025-09-24T02:10:44.427580
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/private-defence-firms-poised-to-grow-16-18-in-fy26-order-books-seen-at-rs-55000-crore-crisil/articleshow/124067343.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
An analysis of over 25% private defence companies rated by Crisil, which together account nearly half the industry revenue, showed steady profitability with operating margins set to remain in the 18-19% range. Order books are expected to rise to about Rs 55,000 crore by the end of FY26, marking a 37.5% jump from the Rs 40,000 crore reported in FY25, propelled by electronic warfare systems, C4 systems and aerospace equipment.
Also read: Rs 1 lakh crore boom! Maruti Suzuki biggest GST winner as shares rally 26%. Late to buy now?
The industry has benefited from sizable equity infusions of around Rs 3,600 crore over the past three fiscals, largely through IPOs and private equity, on a net worth base of Rs 4,760 crore at the end of FY22. “While a third of this funding supported working capital needs, nearly half was directed towards capex, R&D and innovation, bolstering capabilities and helping firms secure larger orders,” Jayashree Nandakumar, Director at Crisil Ratings, said.
Crisil noted that companies are likely to invest to Rs 1,000 crore on capex and incremental working capital in FY26, mostly funded to internal accruals. This would eventually translate to low debt levels, the Crisil report added. The total outside liabilities to tangible net worth ratio is seen stable at about 1.15 times as on March 31, 2026, while interest coverage is expected to improve to 5.5 times from 5.2 times last fiscal.
Government initiatives such as Atmanirbhar Bharat, the Defence Acquisition Policy and the Defence Production and Export Promotion Strategy, along with the Emergency Procurement Plan, are expected to keep order flows strong and support exports.
Crisil cautioned that changes in defence policies, semiconductor supplies and elongation of working capital cycles remain key monitorables.
Echoing the same optimism, last week brokerage firm Incred Equities highlighted the sector’s structural tailwinds, citing the Defence Ministry’s updated Technology Perspective and Capability Roadmap (TPCR-2025), which has expanded the list of procurement programmes to 457 items from 221 in 2018. The roadmap prioritises electronics, electronic warfare and space-based systems over large platforms, with nearly half of all entries tied to digital and cyber capabilities.
Read more: AI, data centre-themed smallcap multibagger stock doubles in 6 months. Should you buy?
“The future of Indian defence is digital, networked, and electronic,” Incred said. It highlighted the Rs 4 trillion Sudarshan Chakra project, a 10-year integrated air and space defence programme involving layered missile defence, advanced radars, high-altitude pseudo-satellites, directed-energy weapons and AI-driven command systems.
