Transcript
Hi, you're listening to ET Markets Radio. I am your host, Neha Vashishth. Welcome to a fresh episode of ET Market Watch -- where we bring you the latest news from the world of stock markets every single day. Let's get to it:
Indian markets slid for the third straight day.
Sensex closed down 57 points at 82,102, while Nifty slipped 33 points to 25,169, falling below the 25,200 mark.
IT stocks stayed under pressure, extending a 3% loss from Monday, after Trump’s shock move to slap a $100,000 fee on H-1B visas. Investors fear this could squeeze margins for India’s top tech firms.
Bright spot? Auto stocks gained 0.6%, riding on strong festive demand during Navratri and recent GST cuts. Banks also edged higher, up 0.4%.
Globally, markets held firm with Europe in the green and Wall Street futures pointing higher, though China dragged Asia lower. Meanwhile, the rupee hit a record low of 88.79 per dollar, before settling at 88.75, its steepest fall in nearly a month.
In commodities, Brent crude held near $66.7 a barrel as Iraq moved closer to restarting a key pipeline.
